'''''Road to Moscow''''' is a 1984 video game published by Ba'rac Limited.

==Gameplay==
''Road to Moscow'' is a game in which the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Russian Front]] of World War II is simulated in a strategic level game.<ref name="CGW18"/>

==Development==
The game's designer was Phil Gardocki.<ref name="PR"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Gary|last=Fields|url=https://archive.org/details/commodore-power-play-19/page/n41/mode/2up|title=Road to Moscow Review|magazine=[[Commodore Power/Play]]|pages=40,126|date=February 1986|accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref>

==Reception==
Bill Wise reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "The combination of ease of play, interesting scenarios, an excellent game system, and numerous strategic options will keep me playing RTM for a long time to come."<ref name="CGW18">{{cite magazine |last=Wise |first=Bill |url=http://pdf.textfiles.com/zines/CGW/1984_0910_issue18.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205071814/http://pdf.textfiles.com/zines/CGW/1984_0910_issue18.pdf|title=Road to Moscow: A Review |magazine=Computer Gaming World |archivedate=February 5, 2009|date=October 1984 |volume=1 |issue=18 |pages=33â€“34}}</ref>

[[Compute!'s Gazette]] praised the game saying "It is one of the best computer war games available" that simulates one of the most interesting wars of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/1984-12-computegazette/page/n85/mode/2up|title=Road to Moscow Review|magazine=[[Compute!'s Gazette]]|pages=83, 84|date=December 1984|accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref>  

A spiritual successor to the game also titled ''Road to Moscow'' was in development by Battlefield Design Group with Arsenal Publishing as the publisher.<ref name="PR"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Scott|last=Udell|url=http://www.cdmag.com/articles/001/024/road_to_moscow_review.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030522160438/http://www.cdmag.com/articles/001/024/road_to_moscow_review.html|title=Road to Moscow Preview|magazine=[[Computer Games Magazine]]|archivedate=May 22, 2003|accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> It was originally scheduled to be released in late 1996<ref name="PR"/> but was pushed to Summer 1998 when the game switched publishers(from Arsenal to [[Interactive Magic]]).<ref>{{cite web|first=Jason|last=Ocaampo|url=http://www.cdmag.com/articles/010/039/road_to_moscow_picked_up.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030523234727/http://www.cdmag.com/articles/010/039/road_to_moscow_picked_up.html|title=Road to Moscow goes through North Carolina|magazine=[[Computer Games Magazine]]|archivedate=May 23, 2003|date=February 2, 1998|accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Scott|last=Udell|url=http://www.cdmag.com/articles/010/128/road_to_moscow_preview.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030523232805/http://www.cdmag.com/articles/010/128/road_to_moscow_preview.html|title=Road to Moscow Preview|magazine=[[Computer Games Magazine]]|archivedate=May 23, 2003|date=March 3, 1998|accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref> As of 1999, the game was still in development but was ultimately never released.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Lackey|url=http://www.cdmag.com/articles/018/007/road2m_preview.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030524221401/http://www.cdmag.com/articles/018/007/road2m_preview.html|title=Road to Moscow Preview|magazine=[[Computer Games Magazine]]|archivedate=May 24, 2003|date=February 23, 1999|accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/1999/02/20/road-to-moscow|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20201028101159/https://www.ign.com/articles/1999/02/20/road-to-moscow|title=Road to Moscow|website=[[IGN]]|archivedate=October 28, 2020|date=February 20, 1999|accessdate=December 14, 2023}}</ref>

